col3:
cited in Humphrey; 
John H. Humphrey: Roman Circuses: Arenas for Chariot Racing. University of California Press, Berkeley and Los Angeles 1986, .
  no online circus-specific information found.

cited in Humphrey;  approximate location; 
[Cherchell] The Circus | Cherchel at circusmaximus.us.
  neither the form nor any original structure is visible.

cited in Humphrey;  approximate location confirmed by old air photographs (90% of the circus has now been built over); 
[Setif] The Circus | Circus at Setif at circusmaximus.us.
  only the southern, curved, end remains visible; U-shaped; approximate (formerly visible) track length: c450m;  approximate (formerly visible) track width: c70m.

cited in Humphrey;  visible track length: 300-350 m; 
[Antinopolis] Wikimapia location: Antinopolis.
  visible track width: c45m;  U-shaped; the carceres are c50m beyond the ends of the ascending seating at the open south-west end; clearly visible and unobstructed.

location information; [Camulodunum] THE ROMAN CIRCUS VICTRICENSIS IN COLCHESTER .  archaeological information; 
[Camulodunum] Colchester Archaeological Trust.
  official archaeological information; 
[Camulodunum] Roman Circus 200 m south of Abbey House, EHER/SMR Number 46327 at Unlocking Essex's Past website from Heritage Conservation at Essex County Council.
  length: c450m;  width: c75m.

cited in Chase;  archaeological city plan; [Gortyn] Map of Gortyn (Gortina - Planta Archaeologica Dela Citta) at romanaqueducts.info | Roman Aqueducts  | AQUASITE: Information on 50 selected Roman aqueducts | Gortyn(a) (Greece / Crete).  visible track length: c375m; 
[Gortyn] Wikimapia location: Gortyn Roman circus.
  visible track width: c50m;  U-shaped plan form clearly visible; space 30% open agricultural land, 70% covered by orchard trees.

referred to as a stadium; 
[Nicopolis] Wikimapia location: Nicopolis Roman circus.
  very small for a circus; visible track length: c215m;  visible track width: c20m;  double-U-shaped plan form with both rounded ends clearly visible; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures.

cited in Humphrey;  referred to as a hippodrome; 
[Caesarea Maritima] The Circus | Caesarea at circusmaximus.us.
  on the coast; parallel to the coast; visible track length: c290m; 
[Caesarea Maritima (coastal)] Wikimapia location: Caesarea Maritima Roman circus (coastal).
  visible track width: c45m;  U-shaped plan form clearly visible; structure substantially complete; few modern structures constructed within the space.

c1km inland from the coast; visible track length: c410m; 
[Caesarea Maritima (inland)] Wikimapia location: Caesarea Maritima Roman circus (inland).
  visible track width: c80m;  form substantially visible; apparently U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures.

Cited in Chase;  location; 
[Mediolanum] The Circus | Milan at circusmaximus.us.

[Mediolanum] Wikimapia location: Mediolanum Roman circus.
  track length: 460m; 
[Mediolanum] J.H.Humphrey, Roman Circuses, Londra 1986, p.614.  track width: 67/68m;  the principal visible remains are a tower at the north western corner of the circus; 
[Mediolanum] Wikimapia location: Milan Roman circus (tower at the north western corner).
  the main body of the circus lay SSE of this tower.

Visible track length: c490m; 
[Circus of Maxentius] Wikimapia location: Circus of Maxentius, Rome.
  visible track width: c80m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; many parts of the structure are visible.

Track length: c621m; 
[Circus Maximus] Circus Maximus#Republican era.
  track width: c150m;  form substantially visible; U-shaped; the space is practically unoccupied by any modern structures; only a few parts of the structure are visible or remain.

Cited in Humphrey;  Wikimapia location; 
[Circus Varianus] Wikimapia location: Circus Varianus, Rome.
  length: 565m; 
[Circus Varianus] Circo Variano at Italian Wikipedia.
  width: 125m.

cited in Humphrey;  visible track length: c245m; 
[Gerasa] Wikimapia location: Gerasa Roman circus.
  visible track width: c50m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; a great deal of the structure still stands.

cited in Humphrey;  the location is of the archaeological site of the Beirut Hippodrome as given on Wikimapia; 
[Berytus] Wikimapia location: Colonia Iulia Augusta Felix Berytus Roman hippodrome.
  this may, or may not, be the same structure as the circus.

cited in Humphrey;  visible track length: c435m; 
[Tyrus] Wikimapia location: Tyrus Roman circus.
  visible track width: c80m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; a great deal of the structure is still visible.

cited in Humphrey;  located both on and parallel to the sea shore; visible track length: c445m; 
[Leptis Magna] Wikimapia location: Leptis Magna Roman circus.
  visible track width: c75m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; some of the structure is still visible.

cited in Humphrey;  the location is approximately that indicated conjecturally, though with considerable certainty, at; 
[Balsa] O Urbanismo de Balsa Romana (from 8:50; dimensions given at 9:11) at Campo Arqueológico de Tavira.
  that site states the topographic marks of [the circus] permit a reasonably rigorous survey; length: c375m;  width: c80m.

cited in Chase;  visible track length: c330m; 
[Miróbriga] Wikimapia location: Miróbriga Roman circus.
  visible track width: c70m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; little of the structure is still visible.

cited in Humphrey;  the location is a close approximation based on information at; 
[Sirmium] archaeological plan of Roman Sirmium from Sirmium Palatium Imperiale at Carska Palata Sirmium.
  length: c450m; 
[Sirmium] Sirmium#Archeological findings.
  width: c150m;  the structure lies buried some 2-4 m under the current town centre, just to the north of the partially excavated palace; only very small sections have been excavated.

Cited in Humphrey;  visible track length: c400m; 
[Emerita Augusta] Wikimapia location: Emerita Augusta Roman circus.
  visible track width: c85m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped but without the distinctive slanted 'flat' carceres end seen in many other circuses; instead the 'flat' end is slightly rounded; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; much of the structure is still visible.

cited in Humphrey;  very approximate location; 
[Italica] Roman sites by list | Spain | Italica at Imperium Roman sites.
  the circus lies under the centre of the existing old town of Santiponce; nothing is visible; note that the very large amphitheatre at Italica is sometimes referred to as a circus.

cited in Humphrey;  the location of the circus has been confirmed by the excavation, and preservation, of a gate to the circus; 
[Saguntum] Wikimapia location: Saguntum Roman circus.

[Saguntum] Roman sites by list | Spain | Sagunto at Imperium Roman sites.
  the circus lies buried under the existing town; only the gate is visible; 
[Saguntum] Wikimapia location: Saguntum Roman circus (excavated gate).
  length: c350m; 
[Saguntum] Wikimapia location: Saguntum Roman circus (information, including dimensions, in Spanish).
  width: c73m.

cited in Humphrey;  most of the circus lies buried under the existing town; a substantial part of the curved eastern end, and part of the south-western side, are visible; track length: c290m; 
[Tarraco] Roman Art | Public Spectacles architecture | Circus of Tarraco in Tarragona | Roman Circus of Tarraco, at Tarragona at SpanishArts.com.
  track width: c75m.

cited in Humphrey;  there appears to be significant uncertainty about the status, and even name, of Zafra in the Roman era; 
[Zafra] Zafra#Roman era (article accessed: 2012-03-01).
  the town appears to have no significant Roman remains other than those of some 20 Roman villas in the surrounding area;  no online circus-specific information found.

cited in Humphrey;  French maps of Roman Bosra showing the location of the circus (or hippodrome); 
[Bostra] Plan de l'Ancienne Ville de Bosra montrant l'emplacement de tous les monuments connus. B&W, 37 x 25 cm, scale by approximation ~ 1:6,100. Shows in red the boundaries of the site at UNESCO | Ancient City of Bosra.

[Bostra] Plan de Bosra (circus identified as a hippodrome) from In-Depth History | Plan of the City | Plan of the City at Bosracity.com | English.
  visible track length: c430m; 
[Bostra] Wikimapia location: Nova Trajana Bostra Roman circus.
  visible track width: c110m;  form clearly visible; U-shaped; the space is virtually unoccupied by any modern structures; much of the structure still stands.

Cited in Humphrey;  location; 
[Carthago] The Circus | Carthage Circus at circusmaximus.us.
  length: c500m; 
[Carthago] Wikimapia location: Carthago Roman circus.
  width: c90m;  U-shaped; very little remains visible; partly occupied by modern constructions.

cited in Humphrey;  visible track length: c500m; 
[Thysdrus] Wikimapia location: Thysdrus Roman circus.
  visible track width: c70m;  form lightly visible; U-shaped; the space is unoccupied by any modern structures; little of the structure is still visible.

Double-U-shaped; very substantially preserved; significantly smaller than other circuses; may be considered a stadium or hippodrome rather than a circus; visible track length: c220m; 
[Aphrodisias] Wikimapia location: Aphrodisias Roman circus/hippodrome/stadium.
  visible track width: 35m.

referred to as a stadium; double U-shaped and small; visible track length: c250m; 
[Laodicea on the Lycus] Wikimapia location: Laodicea on the Lycus Roman stadium or circus.
  visible track width: c40m;  form clearly visible; no visible spina; unoccupied by any subsequent construction.
